{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00f1393d-4de8-486e-a154-76d2426dbdc9","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so I can give you guidance directly.\n\nTo publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool**, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<!-- Include a README in the package -->\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\nKey properties:\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `PackageId` | The NuGet package name |\n\nThen **pack and publish**:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUsers install it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```\n\nNeed me to scaffold the actual project files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a46f2a89-bf4c-42b9-9566-b1b4badda515","outputTokens":473,"requestId":"F3CB:9B30C:126A69:17207F:69F54EC9"},"id":"4407021f-7934-46bf-961f-0ea974e87ee9","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:09:38.022Z","parentId":"a65da1c9-57ba-44d3-a76e-14048361cbdf"}
